1
0:00:43,160 --> 0:00:45,600
在制作蓝色星球Ⅱ的过程中
In the course of making Blue Planet II,

2
0:00:45,680 --> 0:00:49,400
我们探遍了海底世界的每一个角落
we've explored every corner of the underwater world.

3
0:00:51,640 --> 0:00:54,600
我们遇到了不可思议的动物
We've encountered extraordinary animals,

4
0:01:01,000 --> 0:01:06,160
并且对于生命如何在水下生活 有了新的见解
and discovered new insights into how life is lived beneath the waves.

5
0:01:12,280 --> 0:01:16,400
许多年以来 我们都以为海洋浩瀚无穷
For years we thought that the oceans were so vast

6
0:01:16,480 --> 0:01:19,800
海洋生物无数
and the inhabitants so infinitely numerous

7
0:01:19,880 --> 0:01:23,400
所以我们怎样都不会对它们造成影响
that nothing we could do could have an effect upon them.

8
0:01:23,480 --> 0:01:25,560
可如今我们意识到我们错了
But now we know that was wrong.

9
0:01:26,400 --> 0:01:31,800
海洋正面临着人类史上前所未有的威胁
The oceans are under threat now as never before in human history.

10
0:01:33,360 --> 0:01:35,320
在最后一集里
In this final episode,

11
0:01:35,400 --> 0:01:40,520
我们将与试图扭转乾坤的先驱者们对话
we will meet the pioneers who are striving to turn things around.

12
0:01:45,280 --> 0:01:50,160
那些人正致力于保护海洋
People who are helping to save the ocean's most vulnerable inhabitants

13
0:01:52,520 --> 0:01:56,760
以及拯救海洋中最脆弱生物
and dedicating their lives to protecting the seas.

14
0:01:59,640 --> 0:02:01,840
但这一切还来得及吗
But is time running out?

15
0:02:03,920 --> 0:02:08,400
许多人认为我们的海洋已经接近危机边缘了
Many people believe that our oceans have reached a crisis point.

16
0:02:08,920 --> 0:02:12,720
那么究竟 我们的蓝色星球有多脆弱呢
So just how fragile is our blue planet?

17
0:02:28,360 --> 0:02:31,320
冬日的北极圈
Winter in the Arctic Circle.

18
0:02:33,600 --> 0:02:37,000
每一年 挪威的水域都拥有
Every year, the waters of Norway are the setting

19
0:02:37,080 --> 0:02:40,560
最壮丽的野生海洋生物奇观之一
for one of the greatest wildlife spectacles in the ocean.

20
0:02:41,960 --> 0:02:46,320
超过十亿的鲱鱼会涌入这片海域
Over a billion herring pour into these fields.

21
0:02:48,400 --> 0:02:51,320
蓝色星球Ⅱ的团队耗费三年时间
The Blue Planet II team spent three years

22
0:02:51,400 --> 0:02:53,920
只为记录这一奇观
documenting this astonishing event.

23
0:02:58,360 --> 0:03:01,760
大量的猎物吸引着
Such a wealth of prey attracts predators

24
0:03:01,840 --> 0:03:03,880
数不胜数地捕食者
in extraordinary numbers.

25
0:03:07,160 --> 0:03:08,600
虎鲸
Orcas

26
0:03:13,600 --> 0:03:15,520
和座头鲸
and humpback whales.

27
0:03:36,120 --> 0:03:40,520
但事实上 此类迁徙并不总是如此庞大
But this migration hasn't always been so bountiful.

28
0:03:41,440 --> 0:03:45,400
列夫 诺塔斯泰德是一位挪威的渔业科学家
Leif Notastad is a Norwegian fisheries scientist.

29
0:03:46,240 --> 0:03:49,000
这是几世纪以来 对于整条挪威海岸
It's been one of the most important fisheries

30
0:03:49,120 --> 0:03:52,800
最为重要的捕鱼计划之一
that we had for centuries along the whole coast of Norway.

31
0:03:52,880 --> 0:03:54,880
但在十九世纪六十年代末
But in the late 1960s

32
0:03:54,960 --> 0:03:58,760
这附近的鲱鱼曾濒临灭绝
the herrings that we see around us here was on the brink of collapse.

33
0:04:03,560 --> 0:04:06,560
50年以前 捕鱼行动过于频繁
50 years ago, fishing was so intensive

34
0:04:06,640 --> 0:04:09,320
导致鲱鱼几近消失
that the herring had all but disappeared.

35
0:04:11,680 --> 0:04:13,920
当年 数以千计的虎鲸
Orcas were seen as rivals

36
0:04:14,000 --> 0:04:16,120
因被视作竞争对手而遭到捕杀
and hundreds of them were killed.

37
0:04:23,040 --> 0:04:27,400
直到挪威政府下严令管制后
It was only after the Norwegian government imposed severe restrictions

38
0:04:27,480 --> 0:04:29,680
鲱鱼的数量才开始回升
that the herring began to recover.

39
0:04:36,200 --> 0:04:40,960
这一次 同样也会是一场收获丰盈的捕鱼行动
Today, this is once again an immensely productive fishery,

40
0:04:41,840 --> 0:04:45,240
由科学家密切监视着
closely monitored by teams of scientists.

41
0:04:48,960 --> 0:04:51,280
海洋生物学家伊芙 乔尔戴恩
Marine biologist Eve Jourdain

42
0:04:51,360 --> 0:04:54,360
是一位驻地虎鲸专家
is one of the resident orca experts.

43
0:04:54,920 --> 0:04:57,920
自1982年 虎鲸在挪威被下令保护时起
From 1982, orcas got protected in Norway

44
0:04:58,000 --> 0:05:02,640
这里就拥有了全世界最大的虎鲸种群之一
and we have clearly one of the largest orca population in the world out here.

45
0:05:05,040 --> 0:05:07,880
这里如今有超过一千只虎鲸
There are now over a thousand orcas here.

46
0:05:08,080 --> 0:05:11,560
但恰恰因为这里捕食者众多 包括我们在内
But with so many mouths to feed, including ours,

47
0:05:11,640 --> 0:05:14,240
过去同样的错误能否避免呢
can the mistakes of the past be avoided?

48
0:05:16,520 --> 0:05:18,720
为了回答这个关键的问题
To answer this vital question,

49
0:05:18,800 --> 0:05:22,840
伊芙和她的团队动用了多感官摄像监视器
Eve and her team are using multi sensor camera tags.

50
0:05:25,080 --> 0:05:30,720
通过这些监视器 我们想了解虎鲸是如何与猎物们相互影响的
With the tags we try to see how the orcas interact with their prey.

51
0:05:30,800 --> 0:05:34,320
它们是如何捕猎 如何在水下活动
How they hunt and all about the underwater behaviour

52
0:05:34,400 --> 0:05:36,680
了解一切我们不能从船上观察到的
that we are not able to see from the boat.

53
0:05:38,960 --> 0:05:41,160
监视器必须被安装在
A tag has to be attached

54
0:05:41,240 --> 0:05:43,480
虎鲸身上的某个特定位置
to the orca in exactly the right position.

55
0:05:46,520 --> 0:05:48,720
它来了 它来了
Here it goes. Here it comes.

56
0:05:52,960 --> 0:05:54,840
哦 那一下非常准
Oh, that's a good shot.

57
0:05:59,160 --> 0:06:02,120
这是最不具有侵略性的方式了 那上面是个吸盘
It is the least invasive method. It is suction cups.

58
0:06:02,280 --> 0:06:04,720
所以它不会是在虎鲸身上留下伤痕
So it is not a scratch on the whale afterwards

59
0:06:04,800 --> 0:06:06,520
这一点我们非常欣赏
which is something we really like.

60
0:06:09,880 --> 0:06:11,720
在观察虎鲸期间
While studying the orcas,

61
0:06:11,800 --> 0:06:15,320
伊芙注意到了虎鲸行为上一个令人担忧的改变
Eve noticed a worrying change in their behaviour.

62
0:06:16,240 --> 0:06:19,440
它们已经找到了最轻而易举获得食物的方法
They had worked out the easiest way to get a meal.

63
0:06:20,840 --> 0:06:23,080
我们观察到 虎鲸们只是在等待
EVE: We have seen that the orcas are waiting

64
0:06:23,160 --> 0:06:25,640
那些捕鱼船洒下渔网
for those fishing boats to drop the net.

65
0:06:27,080 --> 0:06:28,960
那渔网好似一个晚餐铃
It acts like a dinner bell

66
0:06:29,040 --> 0:06:31,880
一洒下来 虎鲸就都聚集了过来
and then all the orcas of the area gather.

67
0:06:32,840 --> 0:06:34,600
许多鲱鱼会从渔网缝隙中滑出
Quite a lot of herring slip from the net

68
0:06:34,680 --> 0:06:37,320
虎鲸就会抓紧时间捡漏
and this is exactly what the orcas are looking for.

69
0:06:40,760 --> 0:06:45,000
但如伊芙所见 这种新的捕猎窍门是很危险的
But this new tactic is dangerous, as Eve has witnessed.

70
0:06:46,280 --> 0:06:49,280
我们在那里观测到了虎鲸的行为
We were there to monitor the behaviour of the orcas

71
0:06:49,360 --> 0:06:51,520
它们以漏网之鱼而食
scavenging around the nets.

72
0:06:51,600 --> 0:06:54,600
而且我们还发现 有一只大的成年雄性虎鲸
And we realised that one large adult male

73
0:06:54,680 --> 0:06:56,720
居然被渔网缠住了
was actually trapped inside the net.

74
0:06:57,800 --> 0:07:00,080
当渔民想要收回渔网时
When the fishermen started to retrieve the net

75
0:07:00,160 --> 0:07:02,760
虎鲸显然开始慌了
the orca was obviously starting to panic

76
0:07:02,840 --> 0:07:06,000
他在拼尽全力拉拽渔网
and trying to pull as much as he could.

77
0:07:06,080 --> 0:07:08,520
这只虎鲸真的是在为自己的生命而战
This orca was really fighting for his life.

78
0:07:10,680 --> 0:07:13,000
根据条令 渔民必须在得到批准后
Stringent rules require fishermen

79
0:07:13,080 --> 0:07:15,840
才能打开渔网
to get permission before they open their nets.

80
0:07:17,680 --> 0:07:19,200
但获得审批需要时间
But that took time.

81
0:07:24,080 --> 0:07:26,000
等待的过程真的很漫长
EVE: It was such a long process.

82
0:07:26,720 --> 0:07:30,840
我们都以为那头虎鲸要力竭而亡了
We thought that the whale was going to die of exhaustion.

83
0:07:34,640 --> 0:07:37,400
幸运的是 渔民终于获得了批准
Thankfully, the fishermen finally got the clearance

84
0:07:37,480 --> 0:07:40,960
解开渔网 并释放了精疲力尽的虎鲸
to release their net freeing the exhausted orca.

85
0:07:52,280 --> 0:07:56,960
看到它终于存活了下来 回到了族群里
It was a huge relief to see that this orca made it until the end

86
0:07:57,040 --> 0:07:59,600
我们都长舒了一口气
and finally got back to his family.

87
0:08:02,800 --> 0:08:06,600
当海洋哺乳动物与人类存在直接竞争关系时
With marine mammals and humans competing so directly

88
0:08:06,680 --> 0:08:08,920
此类意外是不可避免的
accidents are inevitable.

89
0:08:13,320 --> 0:08:15,800
一只虎鲸被跟踪两天后
Two days after tagging an orca,

90
0:08:15,880 --> 0:08:18,720
它身上跟踪器脱落 伊芙会将它回收
it's released and Eve collects it.

91
0:08:22,200 --> 0:08:24,280
你知道的 这只跟踪器里全是秘密
This tag is full of secrets, you know,

92
0:08:24,360 --> 0:08:26,560
因为它已经追踪虎鲸几天了
because it has been on the whale for several days

93
0:08:26,640 --> 0:08:29,800
它将会完全展示这只虎鲸的所有行踪
and will just reveal exactly what the whales have been doing.

94
0:08:30,440 --> 0:08:34,760
虎鲸的捕猎技巧在影像里完整展现
Pictures from the tag reveal the hunting technique in detail.

95
0:08:41,240 --> 0:08:44,160
它们会潜入鱼群下方
They dive below the ball of fish

96
0:08:47,000 --> 0:08:48,800
然后做一个后空翻
and then back flip.

97
0:08:52,120 --> 0:08:56,040
用尾巴打晕鱼群中的鱼
The tail slap stuns the herring.

98
0:08:58,520 --> 0:09:02,600
伊芙甚至可以数清虎鲸会吃掉多少鲱鱼
Eve can even work out how many fish the orcas are taking.

99
0:09:03,400 --> 0:09:07,360
单单一次甩尾 它们就能杀死近30只鲱鱼
EVE: They can kill up to 30 herring with just one tail slap.

100
0:09:07,440 --> 0:09:09,320
更令人惊讶的是
And then what is pretty amazing is

101
0:09:09,400 --> 0:09:12,440
捕食团队里的虎鲸会一起分享死鱼
all the individuals of the group share the dead herring.

102
0:09:14,000 --> 0:09:16,760
而这里的捕食者 也并不是只有虎鲸
And it's not just the orcas feeding here...

103
0:09:18,920 --> 0:09:22,440
座头鲸也被这场盛宴吸引而来
Humpback whales are also drawn to the feast.

104
0:09:35,880 --> 0:09:38,320
它们也会被摄像头所监视
They too are being tagged and monitored

105
0:09:38,400 --> 0:09:40,360
渔业科学家列夫便能从中
giving fishery scientist Leif

106
0:09:40,440 --> 0:09:43,880
准确得知它们吃了多少鲱鱼
a complete picture of how much herring is being eaten.

107
0:09:44,840 --> 0:09:48,680
鲸鱼们捕食的数量不到鲱鱼总量的1%
The whales, they take probably less than 1%.

108
0:09:49,680 --> 0:09:52,920
渔民的捕量不超过10%
The fishermen take less than 10%.

109
0:09:53,640 --> 0:09:57,440
所以这里的生态平衡是有足够保障的
So the balance there is that there is enough for everybody.

110
0:09:57,520 --> 0:10:00,400
只要我们能继续保持
Given that we manage to stock in sustainable

111
0:10:00,480 --> 0:10:02,320
长期可持续的发展方法
and a long term sustainable way.

112
0:10:11,480 --> 0:10:15,960
但据估 有将近三分之一的海洋渔场
But it's estimated that almost a third of ocean fisheries

113
0:10:16,040 --> 0:10:18,160
正在被过度打捞
are being over exploited.

114
0:10:22,480 --> 0:10:25,240
这里鲱鱼数量上的显著恢复就证明了
The remarkable recovery of the herring here

115
0:10:25,320 --> 0:10:29,160
一个渔场是可以被精心管理 重回生机的
demonstrates what can happen if a fishery is carefully managed.

116
0:10:47,080 --> 0:10:50,200
我们粗鲁对待海洋有很多负面影响
Our maltreatment of the seas has many effects.

117
0:10:52,000 --> 0:10:53,640
有一些是可以推测的
Some are predictable,

118
0:10:54,680 --> 0:10:58,360
但还有一些是完全出人意料的
but there are others that are rather more surprising.

119
0:11:07,040 --> 0:11:08,720
东南亚
Southeast Asia.

120
0:11:10,960 --> 0:11:14,960
这里的珊瑚礁是全世界最丰富的
The coral reefs here are among the richest on the planet.

121
0:11:25,000 --> 0:11:27,680
海洋生物学家史蒂夫 辛普森
Marine biologist Steve Simpson,

122
0:11:27,760 --> 0:11:30,680
正在探索 声音对于
is discovering how important sound is

123
0:11:30,760 --> 0:11:34,200
住在繁荣珊瑚区的动物有多重要
to the animals that live in these bustling coral cities.

124
0:11:35,920 --> 0:11:38,400
直到现在 通过聆听海底 我们才意识到
STEVE: We're only now just realising by listening underwater

125
0:11:38,430 --> 0:11:40,440
鱼儿们在发出各种各样的声音
that the fish are making all these sounds.

126
0:11:40,720 --> 0:11:43,360
它们用声音求偶
They use sound to attract a mate.

127
0:11:43,440 --> 0:11:45,600
用声音尝试着吓跑捕食者
To try and scare away a predator.

128
0:11:46,720 --> 0:11:50,560
你能听到爆裂声 咕哝声 咯咯声 以及噼啪声
You hear pops and grunts and gurgles and snaps.

129
0:11:53,160 --> 0:11:54,960
海底蕴藏着一整套
There's a whole language underwater

130
0:11:55,040 --> 0:11:57,440
我们才刚刚开始了解的语音
that we're only just starting to get a handle on.

131
0:12:16,880 --> 0:12:20,880
利用先进的多方位水下声音探测器
Using an advanced multi directional hydrophone,

132
0:12:20,960 --> 0:12:24,800
史蒂夫想用通过分辨每种声音的来源
Steve is trying to make sense of this extraordinary chorus

133
0:12:24,880 --> 0:12:28,600
来了解这个非凡的合唱团
by working out who is making which noise.

134
0:12:31,520 --> 0:12:34,480
有一种鱼尤其健谈
One fish is especially talkative.

135
0:12:37,360 --> 0:12:40,440
它们应该是珊瑚礁里最著名的居民
It's perhaps the reef's most famous resident.

136
0:12:41,560 --> 0:12:43,040
小丑鱼
The clownfish.

137
0:12:45,720 --> 0:12:47,520
在拍摄此系列时
While filming for the series,

138
0:12:47,600 --> 0:12:51,840
我们锁定了鞍背小丑鱼一家
we followed this particular family of saddleback clownfish

139
0:12:51,920 --> 0:12:55,160
跟随它们一起搜寻产卵的合适场所
as they search for a suitable place to lay their eggs.

140
0:12:58,640 --> 0:13:01,000
真的是挺闹腾的
It's a noisy affair.

141
0:13:15,800 --> 0:13:18,040
对于小丑鱼 声音代表了一切
For clownfish sound really is everything.

142
0:13:18,120 --> 0:13:20,600
它们整天都在相互交谈
They spend all day talking to each other.

143
0:13:21,360 --> 0:13:23,160
有指挥的语气 也有服从的口吻
You've got dominance and submission.

144
0:13:23,240 --> 0:13:25,400
你能听到各式各样的呼唤
You've got all the others calling to each other.

145
0:13:27,120 --> 0:13:30,080
它们似乎也用声音保护自己
It seems that they also use sound

146
0:13:31,240 --> 0:13:36,000
免受来自珊瑚礁附近狩猎者的侵犯
in protecting themselves from the many predators that hunt around the reef.

147
0:13:41,920 --> 0:13:44,520
包括珊瑚石斑鱼
Including coral trout.

148
0:13:58,360 --> 0:14:02,080
这个鳟鱼道具会骗到小丑鱼吗
Will this model trout fool the clownfish?

149
0:14:08,480 --> 0:14:11,040
它们几乎立即有了反应
They react almost immediately.

150
0:14:13,600 --> 0:14:15,080
开始模仿捕食者
By mimicking a predator,

151
0:14:15,160 --> 0:14:20,200
史蒂夫在不威胁它们生存的前提下 设法记录他们的警报语言
Steve manages to record their alarm calls without putting them at risk.

152
0:14:21,160 --> 0:14:24,480
当雌性小丑鱼试图吓跑珊瑚珊瑚石斑鱼时
You can really hear the deeper pulsing sound of the female

153
0:14:24,560 --> 0:14:27,000
你能听到她更深沉的脉冲音波
as she tries to scare the coral trout away.

154
0:14:28,760 --> 0:14:31,120
而所有孩子只是跳出来 不断跳跃 跳跃 跳跃
And all the little ones are just popping... Pop, pop, pop.

155
0:14:31,200 --> 0:14:33,480
仿佛在说 我很好 我还活着呢
As if to say, "I'm still okay. I'm still alive."

156
0:14:35,320 --> 0:14:38,520
它们为了保护自己的家园
So they've got this real language of sounds that they're using

157
0:14:38,600 --> 0:14:42,090
已经掌握了这种真实存在的语言 去抵抗珊瑚珊瑚石斑鱼的入侵
just to try and defend the colony against this coral trout.

158
0:14:45,120 --> 0:14:48,760
但这一发现引发了我们深深的担忧
But that discovery has led to a serious worry.

159
0:14:51,880 --> 0:14:55,040
这些鱼真的把掠食者吓跑了
The fish were really popping away at the predator.

160
0:14:55,120 --> 0:14:58,720
但是 一旦船过来 它们就显得无所适从
But as soon as the boat came over they looked completely distracted.

161
0:14:58,800 --> 0:15:01,800
这所有的噪音完全改变了鱼类的行为
With all that noise it completely changed how the fish were behaving.

162
0:15:03,480 --> 0:15:06,680
它们无法发出比船更大的声音
Unable to make themselves heard above the noise of boats,

163
0:15:06,760 --> 0:15:09,400
家人们不能再互相发出危险警报
the family can't warn each other of danger.

164
0:15:09,480 --> 0:15:12,320
所以他们现在很容易受到攻击
And so they are now vulnerable to attack.

165
0:15:13,600 --> 0:15:15,600
你可以想想有多少船正在驶过
You think about how many boats are driving around.

166
0:15:15,680 --> 0:15:18,560
所有的船只 所有的海上钻井
All of the ships, all of the offshore drilling.

167
0:15:18,640 --> 0:15:20,400
我们在海洋中产生的所有噪音
All the noise that we're making in the ocean

168
0:15:20,480 --> 0:15:22,400
你就能意识到我们淹没了多少
you realise just how much we're drowning out

169
0:15:22,480 --> 0:15:24,400
这种自然界生物所发出声音
this natural biological noise,

170
0:15:24,480 --> 0:15:28,440
并掠夺了动物们交流的能力
robbing animals of their ability to be able to talk to each other.

171
0:15:32,240 --> 0:15:36,840
所有的噪音都可能对许多珊瑚礁鱼造成严重的困扰
All this noise may have serious consequences for many reef fish

172
0:15:36,920 --> 0:15:41,080
这是因为所有的鱼宝宝们 自孵出之时就被卷入海中
because their babies, as soon as they hatch are swept out to sea.

173
0:15:45,000 --> 0:15:48,760
在那里 它们长到足够强壮 才能回来
There they feed and grow until strong enough to swim back.

174
0:15:50,720 --> 0:15:54,640
而它们正是用声音寻找礁石
And to find the reef, they use sound.

175
0:15:55,720 --> 0:15:58,680
它们会倾听 捕捉所有它们能听到的声音
They listen in. They eavesdrop to the noises that they can hear

176
0:15:58,760 --> 0:16:01,960
并使用这一技能 去选择在哪块礁石上建造自己的家园
and they use that to choose which reef they want to make their home.

177
0:16:02,160 --> 0:16:04,720
但显然我们给海洋带来如此多的噪音
But obviously because we're adding all this noise to the ocean

178
0:16:04,800 --> 0:16:07,200
它们如果还能听到礁石的声音 那就真是奇迹了
it's a wonder whether they can even hear the reef at all.

179
0:16:12,400 --> 0:16:16,000
人为的噪音现今已经遍布整个海域
Man-made noise is now everywhere in the ocean.

180
0:16:16,120 --> 0:16:19,760
对所有的海洋生物都产生了影响 
And it has an effect on marine creatures of all kinds.

181
0:16:21,880 --> 0:16:23,840
小至小型鱼
From tiny fish

182
0:16:25,480 --> 0:16:27,840
大到鲸类
to gigantic whales.

183
0:16:31,040 --> 0:16:34,160
但史蒂夫相信会有解决的办法
But Steve believes there are solutions.

184
0:16:34,800 --> 0:16:37,360
海洋噪音确实是个问题
Noise in the ocean is a real problem.

185
0:16:37,440 --> 0:16:39,560
但有些事情我们是可以控制的
But, it's something that we can control.

186
0:16:39,640 --> 0:16:41,160
我们可以选择在何时发出噪音
We can choose where we make the noise.

187
0:16:41,240 --> 0:16:43,160
何地发出噪音
We can choose when we make the noise.

188
0:16:43,240 --> 0:16:46,600
我们也可以直接减少我们制造的噪音量
We can directly reduce the amount of noise that we make

189
0:16:46,680 --> 0:16:48,480
并且我们可以从此刻就做起
and we can start doing that today.

190
0:16:56,480 --> 0:16:58,720
直到现在 我们才开始认识
We're only now beginning to realise

191
0:16:58,800 --> 0:17:02,880
我们制造的声音 对海洋居民造成了什么样的影响
what an impact our noise is having on the inhabitants of the ocean.

192
0:17:05,880 --> 0:17:09,040
其它形式的污染就再熟悉不过了
Other forms of pollution are only too familiar.

193
0:17:16,040 --> 0:17:18,720
塑料问世的一百多年来
Since its invention some hundred years ago,

194
0:17:18,800 --> 0:17:22,680
已经成为我们日常生活中不可或缺的一部分
plastic has become an integral part of our daily lives.

195
0:17:22,760 --> 0:17:26,400
但是 每年约有八百万吨的的塑料
But every year, some eight million tonnes of it

196
0:17:26,480 --> 0:17:28,360
进入海洋中
ends up in the ocean.

197
0:17:28,440 --> 0:17:30,680
而在海中 这些塑料是致命的
And there, it could be lethal.

198
0:17:35,960 --> 0:17:38,240
在蓝色星球Ⅱ的拍摄过程中
While filming Blue Planet II,

199
0:17:38,320 --> 0:17:41,720
船员在每个海域都发现了塑料
the crews found plastic in every ocean.

200
0:17:43,200 --> 0:17:46,400
甚至在最偏远的地方
Even in the most remote locations.

201
0:17:50,920 --> 0:17:52,360
南乔治亚岛
South Georgia.

202
0:17:54,440 --> 0:17:56,880
在南极洲以北900英里处
900 miles north of Antarctica,

203
0:17:56,960 --> 0:18:00,160
这片孤立的荒野
this isolated wilderness is the breeding place

204
0:18:00,240 --> 0:18:03,840
是众多企鹅和象海豹的栖息地
for vast numbers of penguins and elephant seals.

205
0:18:13,960 --> 0:18:16,520
也是空中体形最大的鸟类(信天翁)
It's also a favourite nesting site

206
0:18:16,600 --> 0:18:18,680
最爱的筑巢之地
for the largest bird in the sky.

207
0:18:20,720 --> 0:18:22,640
这是只漂泊的信天翁
A wandering albatross.

208
0:18:26,080 --> 0:18:28,640
在这里 我们了解到远古父母竭尽所能
Here we learn of the extraordinary lengths

209
0:18:28,720 --> 0:18:33,320
给自己的孩子提供最佳的生存机遇
ancient parents go to give their chicks the best chance of survival.

210
0:18:36,080 --> 0:18:40,800
每个伟大的父母都跋涉到千里之外 寻找鱼类和鱿鱼
Each devoted parent travels thousands of miles searching for fish and squid

211
0:18:40,880 --> 0:18:42,800
来喂养它们的孩子
to feed their hungry chick.

212
0:18:46,280 --> 0:18:48,200
尽管它们已竭尽全力
But despite all their efforts,

213
0:18:48,280 --> 0:18:51,280
信天翁的家园仍然陷入了困境
the albatross colony here is in trouble.

214
0:18:53,120 --> 0:18:57,400
露西 奎因是英国南极考察队的一员
Lucy Quinn is part of the British Antarctic Survey team

215
0:18:57,480 --> 0:19:00,960
四十多年来 一直在研究这里的鸟类
studying the birds here for the last 40 years.

216
0:19:02,120 --> 0:19:04,240
只有经过长期的研究
Its only through looking at long terms studies

217
0:19:04,320 --> 0:19:06,760
你才能真正了解这里的生物
that you get a sense of these creatures.

218
0:19:06,840 --> 0:19:11,960
这里的信天翁 在过去的十年里 数量一直在减少
And the albatrosses here have, over the past 10 years, been in decline.

219
0:19:13,440 --> 0:19:16,480
可能有这么几个原因
There are a number of possible reasons.

220
0:19:16,560 --> 0:19:18,320
在海上觅食时
While foraging at sea,

221
0:19:18,400 --> 0:19:22,360
信天翁会被渔具纠缠导致溺死
albatross can get entangled and drowned by fishing gear.

222
0:19:24,120 --> 0:19:26,840
让露西更为担忧的是
But Lucy is particularly alarmed

223
0:19:26,920 --> 0:19:29,960
这些父母究竟为它们的孩子们带回了什么
by what the parents are bringing back for their chick.

224
0:19:30,240 --> 0:19:32,840
信天翁能够咳出
Albatrosses have the ability to cough up

225
0:19:32,920 --> 0:19:35,240
一些不消化的食物
bits of food that they can't digest.

226
0:19:35,320 --> 0:19:38,160
从中我们可以知道它们在吃什么
And from that we can tell what they've been eating.

227
0:19:39,080 --> 0:19:43,240
一只健康小信天翁的饮食中 应该有像鱿鱼之类的食物
A healthy albatross chick in its diet should really have things like squid.

228
0:19:43,320 --> 0:19:47,080
所以我们可以从中找到鱿鱼喙
So we can find the squid beaks that come out of the pellet.

229
0:19:47,160 --> 0:19:50,720
也可以找到一些鱼骨
And also things like fish so we can find fish bones as well.

230
0:19:52,960 --> 0:19:57,520
但这些小信天翁也在被喂食一些 不同寻常的食物
But these chicks are being fed something very different.

231
0:19:58,320 --> 0:20:03,360
我们会发现塑料 这些可怜的雏鸟不得不将这些咳出来
We have some plastic that this poor chick has had to bring up.

232
0:20:04,600 --> 0:20:05,960
塑料袋
Plastic bag.

233
0:20:09,040 --> 0:20:12,160
这是些食品包装袋 看起来像是米饭
Here we have some food packaging. Looks like rice.

234
0:20:12,960 --> 0:20:17,160
幸运的是 这只雏鸟还能把它吐出来
Luckily for this chick, he has managed to get this out of his stomach.

235
0:20:17,240 --> 0:20:20,360
保佑他在换上新羽之前
So, fingers crossed he doesn't have any more plastic left in there

236
0:20:20,440 --> 0:20:21,640
别再吞食更多的塑料了
before he fledges.

237
0:20:25,040 --> 0:20:28,720
对其他雏鸟而言 塑料是可以致命的
For other chicks, plastic can be fatal.

238
0:20:30,640 --> 0:20:33,360
不幸的是 有个塑料牙签
Unfortunately, there is a plastic toothpick

239
0:20:33,440 --> 0:20:35,560
已经穿透这只鸟的胃部
that have actually gone through the stomach.

240
0:20:35,640 --> 0:20:40,000
这么小小的一个东西 实际上就是杀死这只鸟的凶器
Something just as small as that has actually has managed to kill the bird.

241
0:20:40,080 --> 0:20:41,680
看到这些真的很难过
It's really sad to see.

242
0:20:44,120 --> 0:20:49,200
露西收集并记录她在鸟巢周围发现的塑料
Lucy collects and records what plastic she finds around the nests.

243
0:20:52,280 --> 0:20:57,280
这些是上个季度以来 被小鸟吐出来的一些塑料
These are items that were regurgitated just from last season.

244
0:20:57,360 --> 0:21:00,320
这只是其中很小的一部分 实际数量要多得多
And that's gonna be a vast underestimation

245
0:21:00,400 --> 0:21:03,240
因为这些 只是我们碰巧找到的
because that's just ones that we happen to find.

246
0:21:03,320 --> 0:21:07,000
我们没能找到的 还有更多
There'll be many more that we never see being brought back.

247
0:21:10,160 --> 0:21:13,080
为了弄清楚这些垃圾是从哪里来的
To find out where all this rubbish is coming from,

248
0:21:13,160 --> 0:21:18,640
露西和她的团队 在成年鸟类身上 安装了GPS追踪器
Lucy and her team have attached GPS trackers to adult birds.

249
0:21:24,120 --> 0:21:26,800
这些显示了它们要到哪里
It's showing where they're going to find food for themselves

250
0:21:26,880 --> 0:21:29,440
为自己也为后代觅食
and to find food to bring back for their chicks.

251
0:21:30,400 --> 0:21:33,240
这向我们证实了 它们可能正在千里之外
It really shows us that they could be picking up plastic

252
0:21:33,320 --> 0:21:35,720
叼起塑料
from thousands of miles away.

253
0:21:36,480 --> 0:21:39,280
塑料来自于被倾倒进海洋的垃圾
Plastics coming from either being dumped at sea

254
0:21:39,360 --> 0:21:41,960
或者来源于人们家中
or also from people's homes.

255
0:21:42,040 --> 0:21:45,760
塑料进入河流 河流汇入大海
Plastic gets into the rivers and then the rivers flow into the sea.

256
0:21:46,360 --> 0:21:49,920
所以这不仅仅是这个偏远地区的问题
So this isn't just a problem around these remote parts.

257
0:21:50,000 --> 0:21:52,000
更是个世界范围的问题
This is happening worldwide.

258
0:21:52,080 --> 0:21:54,760
是我们的垃圾进入了海洋
And it's our rubbish that's going into the oceans.

259
0:21:54,840 --> 0:21:57,320
这个问题需要我们来解决
It's our problem that we need to solve.

260
0:22:02,040 --> 0:22:03,920
在某些海域
In some parts of the ocean,

261
0:22:04,000 --> 0:22:09,080
每平方英里 就有超过一百万个
it's estimated that there are now over one million pieces of plastic

262
0:22:09,160 --> 0:22:10,840
塑料碎片
for every square mile.

263
0:22:12,160 --> 0:22:13,920
而我们才刚刚认识到
And we're only beginning to discover

264
0:22:14,000 --> 0:22:17,440
这对海洋生物造成了多么严重的影响
just how seriously that affects marine life.

265
0:22:25,040 --> 0:22:27,800
在美国东海岸
On the east coast of the United States,

266
0:22:27,880 --> 0:22:32,960
研究人员正在调研小海豚的神秘死亡事件
researchers are investigating the mysterious deaths of young dolphins.

267
0:22:42,000 --> 0:22:45,480
该小组由莱斯利 哈特博士领导
The team is led by Dr Leslie Hart.

268
0:22:46,600 --> 0:22:48,840
它看起来还很年轻
It looks to be a young animal.

269
0:22:48,920 --> 0:22:50,680
可能就一岁多一点
Maybe a little bit over a year.

270
0:22:50,760 --> 0:22:54,080
我们要试着找出 关于它死亡原因的更多信息
So we're gonna try to find out more information on why this dolphin died.

271
0:23:02,440 --> 0:23:04,840
看着这么小的海豚
Looking at young dolphins...

272
0:23:04,920 --> 0:23:07,640
如此年幼的海豚死去 总是让人心碎
The very young dolphins, it's always heart-breaking.

273
0:23:15,360 --> 0:23:18,080
莱斯利采取组织样本
Leslie takes tissue samples.

274
0:23:18,760 --> 0:23:22,360
他们的化学分析可以提供关键的证据
Their chemical analysis could provide crucial evidence.

275
0:23:23,400 --> 0:23:27,520
这些动物体内检出毒素含量之高
We are often shocked by the high levels of toxins

276
0:23:27,600 --> 0:23:29,400
常常使我们震惊
that we detect in these animals.

277
0:23:30,920 --> 0:23:34,200
这些小海豚死去的原因有很多
These young calves are dying for a number of reasons.

278
0:23:34,280 --> 0:23:38,280
但我们怀疑人造毒素才是主要原因
But we suspect man-made toxins are playing a large role.

279
0:23:40,840 --> 0:23:43,600
塑料可能只是问题的一部分
And plastic could be part of the problem.

280
0:23:53,720 --> 0:23:55,280
塑料一旦进入海洋
Once in the ocean,

281
0:23:55,360 --> 0:23:58,440
就会分解成微小的碎片
plastic breaks down into tiny fragments.

282
0:23:59,320 --> 0:24:01,160
微型塑料
Micro plastics.

283
0:24:04,400 --> 0:24:08,440
所有这些已经排入海洋的化工产品
Along with all the industrial chemicals that have drained into the ocean

284
0:24:08,520 --> 0:24:11,600
形成了潜在的毒性环境
these form a potentially toxic soup.

285
0:24:17,840 --> 0:24:19,760
这些极小的生物体
The really small organisms

286
0:24:19,840 --> 0:24:23,240
会误把这些微型塑料当作食物
can mistake these tiny, tiny plastics as food.

287
0:24:23,320 --> 0:24:26,000
更大些的生物吃这些浮游生物
Then the larger organisms eat the plankton.

288
0:24:26,080 --> 0:24:28,640
然后大鱼吃小鱼
Then the larger fish eat the smaller fish,

289
0:24:28,720 --> 0:24:30,160
一直如此下去
and so on and so forth.

290
0:24:32,200 --> 0:24:35,400
海豚处于这条食物链的顶端
Dolphins are at the top of this food chain

291
0:24:35,480 --> 0:24:39,040
我们现在认为污染物可能在它们的组织中富集
and it's now thought that pollutants may be building up in their tissues

292
0:24:39,120 --> 0:24:44,760
毒性大到 幼崽可以被污染的母乳致死的地步
to such a degree that a mother's contaminated milk could kill her calf.

293
0:25:02,840 --> 0:25:07,200
为了拯救所有的海洋生物
Industrial pollution and the discarding of plastic waste

294
0:25:07,280 --> 0:25:11,600
工业污染物和塑料垃圾必须被处理掉
must be tackled for the sake of all life in the ocean.

295
0:25:27,440 --> 0:25:31,120
在世界各地 人们正在致力于
Around the world, people are now devoting their lives

296
0:25:31,200 --> 0:25:34,400
拯救一些濒危的海洋生物
to saving some of the most threatened sea creatures.

297
0:25:36,480 --> 0:25:39,080
正如这里 加勒比地区
As here in the Caribbean.

298
0:25:42,760 --> 0:25:45,640
在这几座岛上
Every year on just a few islands,

299
0:25:45,720 --> 0:25:48,360
每年都会发生些特别的事情
a remarkable event takes place.

300
0:25:58,120 --> 0:26:00,680
夕阳西下时
As the sun sets,

301
0:26:00,760 --> 0:26:03,760
巨型爬行动物爬上岸来
giant reptiles begin to emerge.

302
0:26:18,040 --> 0:26:21,640
这个雄伟的生物正准备
This magnificent creature preparing...

303
0:26:23,760 --> 0:26:26,200
正准备下蛋
Preparing to lay her eggs

304
0:26:26,280 --> 0:26:29,160
这是所有海龟中体形最大的
is the largest of all turtles.

305
0:26:29,240 --> 0:26:30,600
棱皮龟
A leatherback.

306
0:26:31,520 --> 0:26:35,320
它们可以长到半吨
They can grow up to half a tonne in weight.

307
0:26:35,400 --> 0:26:39,240
并有着可以追溯到一亿年前
And they have an ancestry that goes back a hundred million years

308
0:26:39,320 --> 0:26:41,320
恐龙时代的血统
to the age of the dinosaur.

309
0:26:42,560 --> 0:26:47,680
但近年来 它们的数量呈毁灭型下降
But in recent times their numbers have fallen catastrophically.

310
0:26:48,680 --> 0:26:52,840
然而 在这里 加勒比地区 事情有了转机
Here, however, in the Caribbean there is hope.

311
0:26:57,480 --> 0:26:59,880
棱皮龟离开大海
Leatherback turtles leave the sea

312
0:26:59,960 --> 0:27:03,120
是为了在干燥的沙子里产卵
in order to lay their eggs in the dry sand.

313
0:27:05,520 --> 0:27:10,480
但离开了水 这些巨大的生物很容易成为偷猎者的目标
But out of water, these huge creatures are easy targets for hunters.

314
0:27:14,200 --> 0:27:17,000
在特立尼达岛上的一个小渔村里
In a small fishing village in Trinidad,

315
0:27:17,080 --> 0:27:20,920
伦 彼得斯就曾亲身经历这些
Len Peters has experienced this first hand.

316
0:27:22,200 --> 0:27:26,600
在我家里 吃海龟肉是很正常的事情
I grew up in a household where the presence of turtle meat was normal.

317
0:27:26,680 --> 0:27:28,480
冰箱里总是装满它们
The fridge was always full of it.

318
0:27:28,560 --> 0:27:31,600
所有人 所有人都抓捕海龟 包括我的父母
Everybody... Everybody harvested turtles, including my parents.

319
0:27:32,560 --> 0:27:35,040
当我终有一天接触到
It's only when I became exposed to things

320
0:27:35,040 --> 0:27:37,160
有关棱皮龟的报告时
that were being published about leatherbacks

321
0:27:37,200 --> 0:27:38,680
才知道它们正濒临灭绝
who were on the verge of extinction.

322
0:27:38,700 --> 0:27:40,080
却无人关心
And nobody cares.

323
0:27:40,160 --> 0:27:41,640
这刺激到了我
That piqued my interest.

324
0:27:42,680 --> 0:27:46,720
伦开始以保护棱皮龟为己任
Len took the leatherback's future into his own hands.

325
0:27:48,600 --> 0:27:52,440
为此 他开始晚间到海滩上巡逻
He began patrolling the beach at night to protect the turtles.

326
0:27:53,000 --> 0:27:54,640
这是个十分有勇气的举动
A brave thing to do.

327
0:27:58,360 --> 0:28:01,160
我们遭到了巨大的阻力
We were met with tremendous resistance.

328
0:28:01,240 --> 0:28:03,000
人们会在夜晚攻击我们
People would pelt us at night.

329
0:28:03,080 --> 0:28:05,240
有人辱骂我
I have had persons insult me.

330
0:28:05,320 --> 0:28:06,880
有人诅咒我
I've had persons curse me.

331
0:28:06,960 --> 0:28:11,680
还有人拿着刀要砍我
I've had persons physically try to wrestle me with a machete.

332
0:28:11,760 --> 0:28:14,400
那真是一段很艰难的时光
So it was really a hostile time back then.

333
0:28:14,480 --> 0:28:17,200
如果伦想要拯救这些海龟
If Len was going to save these turtles

334
0:28:17,280 --> 0:28:20,040
他需要赢得整个村子的支持
he needed to win over the whole community.

335
0:28:22,240 --> 0:28:26,480
我们必须找到办法 让村民们
We had to find a way to get the villagers to benefit

336
0:28:26,560 --> 0:28:28,600
感受到这些动物存在的好处
from the presence of these animals.

337
0:28:31,720 --> 0:28:35,440
他开始鼓励游客到海滩来旅游
He began to encourage tourists to visit the beach

338
0:28:35,520 --> 0:28:38,440
并培训一些村民成为导游
and trained some villagers to be their guides.

339
0:28:42,560 --> 0:28:45,120
为保护海龟的未来
To help secure the turtles' future,

340
0:28:45,200 --> 0:28:48,280
他把信息传递给了下一代
he took the message to the next generation.

341
0:28:48,840 --> 0:28:52,840
棱皮龟最大能长到多大
Now what's... What's the largest size a leatherback can grow to?

342
0:28:53,200 --> 0:28:55,280
嗯 沙妮
Uh, Shanie.

343
0:28:55,560 --> 0:28:57,440
- 2000磅 - 答对了
-2,000 pounds. -That's correct.

344
0:28:57,520 --> 0:29:01,280
棱皮龟能够长到2000磅那么大
Leatherbacks can grow to 2,000 pounds.

345
0:29:01,360 --> 0:29:02,920
那的确是一只大海龟
Well, that's a big turtle.

346
0:29:03,560 --> 0:29:05,600
伦的艰苦努力有了回报
Len's hard work paid off.

347
0:29:05,680 --> 0:29:08,000
现在 人们对待海龟的态度已有了转变
And now, attitudes have changed.

348
0:29:11,760 --> 0:29:15,280
我们花了很长时间才取得村民的支持和信任
It took us a while to reach out to the villagers.

349
0:29:15,360 --> 0:29:17,800
但渐渐地 我们也让他们参与进来
But gradually we got them involved as well.

350
0:29:17,880 --> 0:29:20,840
我们让原本要捕杀动物的偷猎者
We got some of the poachers who would be hunting the animals to

351
0:29:21,040 --> 0:29:22,800
转而投入到物保护计划之中
be part of the conservation programme.

352
0:29:25,440 --> 0:29:27,920
在保护成年海龟的同时
As well as protecting the adult turtles,

353
0:29:28,000 --> 0:29:32,280
团队也收集海龟蛋 涨潮时它们可能会被海水淹没
the team also collect any eggs that might be flooded at high tide.

354
0:29:35,320 --> 0:29:38,160
如果这些蛋过于靠近大海
If the eggs are laid too close to the sea,

355
0:29:38,240 --> 0:29:40,840
我们就重选地点把它们埋好
we relocate the eggs and rebury them.

356
0:29:42,200 --> 0:29:44,800
多亏这个村子的不懈努力
Thanks to the efforts of this community,

357
0:29:44,880 --> 0:29:48,400
这些海龟的命运有了翻天覆地的变化
these turtles have had an extraordinary change in fortune.

358
0:29:50,600 --> 0:29:53,120
这里现在被认为是世界上
This is now thought to be one of the densest

359
0:29:53,200 --> 0:29:56,000
最密集的棱皮龟筑巢海滩
leatherback nesting beaches in the world.

360
0:29:59,880 --> 0:30:03,400
在筑巢季的高峰开始时
When we started at the height of the nesting season,

361
0:30:03,480 --> 0:30:07,160
每晚会有30到40只海龟来到这里
the numbers will be 30-40 turtles a night.

362
0:30:07,240 --> 0:30:08,960
现在 已经超过500只了
Now, it's over 500.

363
0:30:09,080 --> 0:30:12,360
在二十年里 我们见证了从每晚的40只
So, we have seen an increase from 40 turtles

364
0:30:12,440 --> 0:30:15,400
到500只海龟的增长
to 500 turtles a night in just around 20 years.

365
0:30:19,040 --> 0:30:22,800
同时也向珍贵的新生小海龟们施以援手
Precious new hatchlings are also given a helping hand.

366
0:30:26,360 --> 0:30:29,440
所有在白天出生的小海龟都会被收集起来
Any that emerge during the day are collected

367
0:30:29,520 --> 0:30:34,240
放归大海 远离饥饿的鸟类
to be released safely back to the sea, away from hungry birds.

368
0:30:41,400 --> 0:30:46,040
待它成年 回归这片孵化它的海滩之前
This little leatherback will have to face a thousand hazards

369
0:30:46,120 --> 0:30:50,480
这只小棱皮龟将会面对千难万险
before it returns as an adult to this beach where it hatched.

370
0:30:51,360 --> 0:30:54,560
而随着人类加剧对海洋的破坏
And those dangers will be greatly increased

371
0:30:54,640 --> 0:30:57,840
这些凶险将会大大增加
because of damage that we have done to the ocean.

372
0:30:59,760 --> 0:31:01,200
祝你好运 小棱皮龟
Good luck, little leatherback.

373
0:31:32,680 --> 0:31:35,040
保护海滩上的繁殖地
Protecting breeding sites on beaches

374
0:31:35,120 --> 0:31:39,560
能够改善一些海洋动物的命运
may improve the fortune of some marine animals,

375
0:31:39,640 --> 0:31:43,800
但当它们在深海中漫游时 提供保护则要困难得多
but safeguarding them while they roam the high seas is much more difficult.

376
0:31:48,800 --> 0:31:51,720
在这里 几乎无法获得保护
Out here, there is little protection.

377
0:32:00,560 --> 0:32:06,600
每个夜晚 数千英里的鱼线上挂满了鱼钩
Every night, thousands of miles of fishing lines laden with hooks are set.

378
0:32:08,960 --> 0:32:12,280
据说 这些鱼线连起来足足能够绕地球两圈
There's enough, it's said, to wrap twice around the world.

379
0:32:17,240 --> 0:32:20,520
大到足以包住大教堂的渔网
Nets large enough to engulf cathedrals

380
0:32:20,600 --> 0:32:23,840
一次可以捕获几百吨鱼
trap hundreds of tonnes of fish at a time.

381
0:32:26,520 --> 0:32:31,160
像鲨鱼这种长途跋涉的旅客尤其危险
Long distance travellers such as sharks are particularly at risk.

382
0:32:37,280 --> 0:32:41,560
据估计 每年大约有几百万只鲨鱼被杀
It's estimated that tens of millions are killed every year,

383
0:32:41,640 --> 0:32:46,440
包括海洋中最大的鱼类 鲸鲨
including the biggest fish in the sea, the whale shark.

384
0:32:58,480 --> 0:33:02,160
鲨鱼生物学家乔纳森 格林担心
Shark biologist Jonathan Green is concerned

385
0:33:02,240 --> 0:33:05,640
留给这些非凡生物的时间已经不多了
that time is running out for these extraordinary creatures.

386
0:33:06,840 --> 0:33:09,560
我们知道它们正在被大规模捕捞
We know that they're being fished possibly at a massive rate.

387
0:33:10,040 --> 0:33:13,480
每年都可能有成千上万的它们被人类捕猎
They may be taken by the thousands, possibly tens of thousands a year.

388
0:33:14,160 --> 0:33:15,880
如果那是真的
If that is indeed true,

389
0:33:15,960 --> 0:33:19,440
我们不知道这种捕鱼压力它们还能承受多久
we don't know how long they can withstand that kind of fishing pressure.

390
0:33:21,240 --> 0:33:24,160
为了拯救它们 乔纳森试着解开
To save them, Jonathan is trying to solve

391
0:33:24,240 --> 0:33:26,880
它们繁衍地点的秘密
the mystery of where they give birth.

392
0:33:32,960 --> 0:33:37,320
并且 第一次 他有了一些确切的线索
And, for the first time, he has a clue as to where this might be.

393
0:33:44,600 --> 0:33:48,680
怀孕的鲸鲨会穿越太平洋
Pregnant whale sharks are thought to be travelling from across the Pacific Ocean

394
0:33:48,760 --> 0:33:51,480
游至加拉帕戈斯群岛中的达尔文岛
to Darwin Island in the Galapagos.

395
0:34:00,160 --> 0:34:02,360
乔纳森打算在一头怀孕的雌性鲸鲨身上
Jonathan is going to try and attach

396
0:34:02,360 --> 0:34:05,920
固定一个多传感器相机
a multi-sensor camera tag to a pregnant female.

397
0:34:06,880 --> 0:34:08,280
好了 准备就绪
Okay. We're good to go.

398
0:34:16,840 --> 0:34:20,000
这些鲨鱼只在那片地区停留几天
These sharks only stay in the area for a few days.

399
0:34:20,960 --> 0:34:22,880
这也许是他唯一的机会
This may be his only chance.

400
0:34:35,160 --> 0:34:40,520
乔纳森必须在鲨鱼潜至危险的深海之前将相机固定好
Jonathan has to attach the tag before the shark dives to dangerous depths.

401
0:34:59,680 --> 0:35:03,000
在自动脱落前
The tag will remain on the giant's fin for two days

402
0:35:03,080 --> 0:35:05,160
相机会在鲨鱼鳍上停留两天
before it's automatically released.

403
0:35:07,840 --> 0:35:11,760
取回来之后 它揭示了一些不寻常的行为
Once retrieved, it reveals some unusual behaviour.

404
0:35:14,440 --> 0:35:15,920
哦 太美了 真美
Oh, beautiful, beautiful.

405
0:35:18,480 --> 0:35:22,840
那有只丝鲨从前面擦过去了 就在她右边
There's a silky rubbing up against the front. Next to her right.

406
0:35:23,240 --> 0:35:26,960
丝鲨在摩擦她粗糙的皮肤
The silky sharks are brushing up against her rough skin,

407
0:35:27,040 --> 0:35:29,320
也许是为了擦掉身上的寄生虫
perhaps to scrape off parasites.

408
0:35:31,160 --> 0:35:35,920
幼鱼无论种类 表层水域都因这些掠食性鲨鱼的存在
These predatory sharks make the surface waters very unsafe places

409
0:35:36,000 --> 0:35:38,200
而变得很不安全
for young fish of any kind.

410
0:35:41,080 --> 0:35:43,280
难题出现了
There is a surprise in store.

411
0:35:45,000 --> 0:35:48,000
跟踪标记的深度传感器显示
The tag's depth sensor reveals that she dived

412
0:35:48,080 --> 0:35:50,720
她潜入了600米深的海中
to a depth of 600 metres.

413
0:35:52,880 --> 0:35:56,320
可下面对于相机来说过于黑暗
But down there, it's too dark for the camera.

414
0:36:02,560 --> 0:36:05,800
乔纳森能够证明它们是否在繁衍的唯一方法
The only way Jonathan can prove if they're giving birth

415
0:36:06,680 --> 0:36:08,480
就是到深海亲自观察
is to go down and look.

416
0:36:32,000 --> 0:36:35,800
一个身影渐渐变得清晰
Out of the gloom, a shape materialises.

417
0:36:38,360 --> 0:36:40,440
另一只大型鲸鲨
Another massive whale shark.

418
0:36:42,320 --> 0:36:45,480
快看看她 她在看我们 她正在看我们
Oh, look at her. She's having a look at us. She's looking right at us.

419
0:36:50,600 --> 0:36:52,640
她真是太大了
She is huge.

420
0:36:52,760 --> 0:36:55,160
看她的肚子 绝对是巨大的
And look at the belly. Absolutely massive.

421
0:36:56,440 --> 0:36:58,200
那是只巨大的雌性怀孕鲸鲨
That's a large pregnant female.

422
0:36:59,160 --> 0:37:01,120
她转身了 她转身了
She's turning around. She's turning around.

423
0:37:07,200 --> 0:37:10,280
这表示我们可以跟着它们 可以在潜艇里跟着它们
Goes to show we can follow them. We can follow them in the submarine.

424
0:37:13,840 --> 0:37:16,880
她带领他们进入了黑暗之中
She leads them down into the darkness.

425
0:37:19,720 --> 0:37:23,720
探测器测量 突破100米 仍在下沉中
Rover control. Passing 100 metres, descending.

426
0:37:26,200 --> 0:37:29,800
一直向下 我想她稍稍加速了
Heading down. I think she's accelerated slightly.

427
0:37:33,520 --> 0:37:35,320
她太快了
She's too fast.

428
0:37:36,360 --> 0:37:40,320
强劲的洋流阻碍了他们 潜艇无法继续前进
And with the strong current running against them, the sub can't keep up.

429
0:37:45,040 --> 0:37:48,680
但是 第一次 乔纳森能够亲眼看见
But, for the first time, Jonathan can see for himself

430
0:37:48,760 --> 0:37:50,600
她前进的目的地
exactly where she's headed.

431
0:37:53,240 --> 0:37:55,320
达尔文岛能够为新生的幼鱼们提供
What specifically Darwin could provide

432
0:37:55,400 --> 0:38:00,160
安全的避难所 捕食者们无法进入
is a safe refuge for those new-born pups where predators can't access.

433
0:38:01,920 --> 0:38:04,560
对于这些穿越大洋的巨人来说
Perfect conditions for the formative years

434
0:38:04,640 --> 0:38:06,480
这里为它们的成长提供了完美的居住环境
of these ocean-travelling giants.

435
0:38:14,360 --> 0:38:15,960
令人难以置信
That was unbelievable.

436
0:38:17,600 --> 0:38:19,360
真是一生的梦想
Dream of a lifetime.

437
0:38:22,080 --> 0:38:24,240
他发现了怀孕的鲸鲨
His discovery that pregnant whale sharks

438
0:38:24,320 --> 0:38:27,280
就在这片深海之中 这是强有力的证据
are visiting this very deep patch of the sea floor

439
0:38:27,360 --> 0:38:31,520
证明这里的确是这些巨人们繁衍下一代的地方
is strong evidence that this is indeed where the giants produce their young.

440
0:38:34,280 --> 0:38:37,680
如果我能证明它们的确出生在这片海域
If I can actually prove that they are giving birth in this area,

441
0:38:37,760 --> 0:38:39,840
我们就拥有了必要的信息
then we'll have the information necessary

442
0:38:39,920 --> 0:38:41,920
可以联系政府 告诉他们
to go to governments and actually say,

443
0:38:42,000 --> 0:38:45,200
"你们必须保护它们迁移的常规路线"
"You must preserve those routes that they're migrating through."

444
0:38:45,280 --> 0:38:48,640
到那时 也只有那时 我们才能真正为这些
And then, and only then, can we really truly afford protection

445
0:38:48,720 --> 0:38:50,800
美丽的大洋旅客提供保护
for this beautiful ocean traveller.

446
0:38:58,680 --> 0:39:00,840
今天 我们只有不到百分之一的
Today, less than one percent

447
0:39:00,920 --> 0:39:03,600
国际水域受到保护
of our international waters are protected.

448
0:39:06,480 --> 0:39:09,880
如果我们要守护多种海洋生物的未来
And the creation of marine reserves is vital

449
0:39:09,960 --> 0:39:13,920
那么海洋保护区的建立就变得至关重要
if we're to safeguard the future of many ocean creatures.

450
0:39:19,800 --> 0:39:22,440
这会需要国际间的合作
It will require international cooperation.

451
0:39:23,880 --> 0:39:25,800
但在这里 也仍有希望
But here, too, there is hope.

452
0:39:28,120 --> 0:39:30,280
我们能够扭转局势
We can turn things around.

453
0:39:31,000 --> 0:39:32,960
我们曾经做过这样的事情
We've done so once before.

454
0:39:33,880 --> 0:39:37,640
几个世纪以来 世界上以海为生的国家
For centuries, the sea-going nations of the world

455
0:39:37,720 --> 0:39:40,680
都在捕杀鲸类 直到它们濒临灭绝
hunted the great whales until they were close to extinction.

456
0:39:41,560 --> 0:39:45,840
之后 在1986年 这些国家一致同意
And then, in 1986, those nations got together

457
0:39:45,920 --> 0:39:49,800
停止商业捕鲸
and agreed to put a stop to commercial whaling.

458
0:39:53,560 --> 0:39:57,320
今天 虽然仍有部分国家继续捕鲸
Today, although a few nations continue to hunt whales,

459
0:39:57,400 --> 0:40:00,160
但有一些鲸数量正在恢复
some of the great whales are making a recovery.

460
0:40:08,520 --> 0:40:11,280
在斯里兰卡周围的热带海域
In the tropical seas surrounding SrI Lanka,

461
0:40:11,360 --> 0:40:14,840
流传着许多有关鲸类聚集的故事
there are stories of vast gatherings of whales.

462
0:40:19,000 --> 0:40:22,480
2009年内战结束后
When the civil war ended in 2009,

463
0:40:22,560 --> 0:40:26,440
当地人重新在这片水域捕鱼
locals here were able once again to fish these waters.

464
0:40:29,200 --> 0:40:32,720
不久这里就有了关于抹香鲸集结的报道
There were soon reports of assemblies of sperm whales,

465
0:40:32,800 --> 0:40:35,960
已有几个世纪都没有见到这种景象了
the likes of which had not been seen for centuries.

466
0:40:38,160 --> 0:40:42,120
海洋向导达亚决心探求
Marine guide Daya was determined to get to the truth

467
0:40:42,200 --> 0:40:44,520
这些渔民故事背后的真相
behind these fishermen's tales.

468
0:40:45,480 --> 0:40:47,720
渔民们告诉我从这里往北一点
The fishermen told me that there are lots of whales

469
0:40:47,800 --> 0:40:49,000
有许多鲸
a little bit north from here.

470
0:40:49,920 --> 0:40:52,320
他们没有告诉我确切的数字
They didn't actually tell me a number,

471
0:40:52,400 --> 0:40:55,760
但数量很大 不止一两只
but in big numbers, not one or twos.

472
0:40:55,840 --> 0:40:57,800
而是有很多
Er, many.

473
0:41:02,280 --> 0:41:04,600
这件事花了他三年时间
It took him three years,

474
0:41:04,680 --> 0:41:09,240
不过最终 他找到了支撑这些传闻的证据
but eventually, he found evidence to support these rumours.

475
0:41:55,720 --> 0:41:59,000
我们看见大约15只抹香鲸从身边经过
We saw about 15 sperm whales go past us.

476
0:42:08,760 --> 0:42:10,800
之后 另外四只也越过我们
Then, another four came past us.

477
0:42:14,160 --> 0:42:17,600
在看见大概40只鲸鱼后 我开始计数
After about 40 then passed me, I started counting.

478
0:42:22,640 --> 0:42:25,080
然而它们接连不断 我都数不过来了
Still, they kept coming, so I lost count.

479
0:42:27,440 --> 0:42:30,480
我估计大概见到了300只抹香鲸
I estimated that we saw about 300 sperm whales.

480
0:42:38,000 --> 0:42:41,960
抹香鲸过去曾遭受大规模捕杀
Sperm whales were once killed in vast numbers

481
0:42:42,080 --> 0:42:44,880
如果这种屠杀仍在继续的话
and it's thought that if the slaughter had continued,

482
0:42:44,960 --> 0:42:48,360
这个物种将会濒临灭绝
the species would be in danger of extermination.

483
0:42:51,640 --> 0:42:56,360
但至少 现在它们仍能在这里以大规模被发现
But now, here at least, they are being seen in huge numbers.

484
0:42:57,840 --> 0:43:01,680
我想它们来这里是为了觅食 交配并养育后代
I believe they come here to feed, mate, and raise their young.

485
0:43:01,800 --> 0:43:04,320
对它们而言这里一定算是个度假区
So, this must be a holiday spot for them, you know.

486
0:43:04,640 --> 0:43:07,960
目前为止 我只知道这世界有这一个地方
At the moment, I don't know of any other place in the world

487
0:43:08,040 --> 0:43:10,760
抹香鲸会有如此大规模的聚集
that, er, sperm whales gather like this.

488
0:43:14,160 --> 0:43:17,800
尽管鲸类数量仍旧在不断衰减
Although some whale populations are still in decline,

489
0:43:17,880 --> 0:43:22,600
但这种景象证明当海洋国家一起努力时
scenes like this prove that when sea-going nations come together,

490
0:43:22,680 --> 0:43:25,720
会产生惊人的结果
they can achieve astonishing results.

491
0:43:33,600 --> 0:43:39,080
但是今天海洋面临着真正全球范围的威胁
But today, the oceans face threats on a truly global scale.

492
0:43:44,840 --> 0:43:46,800
大堡礁
The Great Barrier Reef.

493
0:43:49,240 --> 0:43:52,680
世界上最大的珊瑚礁生态系统
The largest coral reef system in the world.

494
0:43:55,360 --> 0:44:00,640
这里 我们记录的片段展示了鱼类能有多聪明
Here, we filmed stories which reveal just how smart fish can be.

495
0:44:06,320 --> 0:44:09,080
例如 这种机灵的猪齿鱼
This ingenious tuskfish, for example,

496
0:44:09,160 --> 0:44:13,560
用它最喜欢的珊瑚来击开贝类
used a favourite coral anvil to smash open shellfish.

497
0:44:15,840 --> 0:44:19,320
这种奇特的行为曾被
This astonishing behaviour has been closely studied

498
0:44:19,400 --> 0:44:21,840
当地的科学家亚力克斯 维尔 认真的研究过
by local scientist Alex Vail.

499
0:44:23,600 --> 0:44:26,080
我们给它取名叫"珀西" 执着的意思
We're calling Percy "Percy the Persistent"

500
0:44:27,400 --> 0:44:30,600
因为它可能要花一个小时才能敲开第一个贝壳
because he took, like, an hour to open the first shell.

501
0:44:36,040 --> 0:44:38,440
他至少要敲击50次以上
He must have hit it well over 50 times,

502
0:44:38,520 --> 0:44:41,400
不过他依旧会坚持 直到把贝壳砸开
but he just kept on going and finally got it open.

503
0:44:50,840 --> 0:44:53,880
亚力克斯在大堡礁其中一个
Alex grew up on the Great Barrier Reef

504
0:44:53,960 --> 0:44:56,760
叫利泽德的偏远小岛上长大
on one of its more remote islands, Lizard.

505
0:44:59,120 --> 0:45:01,400
他对这里的珊瑚礁非常了解
He knows the reef intimately.

506
0:45:06,720 --> 0:45:10,480
不过 在2016年 拍摄蓝色星球Ⅱ时
But, in 2016, while he was filming for Blue Planet II,

507
0:45:10,560 --> 0:45:13,080
亚力克斯目睹了一场大灾难
Alex witnessed a catastrophe.

508
0:45:15,040 --> 0:45:17,920
拍摄开始的时候 一切都很好
ALEX: When we started filming, everything was pretty much fine.

509
0:45:18,000 --> 0:45:20,080
所有的珊瑚基本都是健康的
All of the corals were basically healthy.

510
0:45:22,200 --> 0:45:25,480
但在最近几周 一切都变了
But in the last few weeks, everything changed.

511
0:45:26,520 --> 0:45:29,240
我之前从未见过这种现象
I have never seen anything like this before.

512
0:45:32,440 --> 0:45:34,600
海洋变暖和一种不可预测的气候事件
A combination of a warming ocean

513
0:45:34,680 --> 0:45:38,280
厄尔尼诺现象的结合
and an unpredictable weather event called El Niño

514
0:45:38,360 --> 0:45:41,000
使海洋温度前所未有地上升
raised sea temperatures to record levels.

515
0:45:46,000 --> 0:45:49,280
这对珊瑚来说是毁灭性的打击
And this had a disastrous effect on the corals.

516
0:45:50,800 --> 0:45:55,040
高温使造礁珊瑚失去了提供营养的藻类
The heat causes reef-building corals to lose their nourishing algae,

517
0:45:56,040 --> 0:45:58,560
白色的骨骼被暴露在外
exposing their white skeletons.

518
0:46:03,440 --> 0:46:07,560
当温度持续上升 白化的珊瑚就会死亡
When temperatures remain high, bleached corals die off.

519
0:46:10,440 --> 0:46:13,400
今年的白化情况是史上最严重的一次
The bleaching this year has been the worst in history

520
0:46:13,480 --> 0:46:14,920
对大堡礁来说
for the Great Barrier Reef.

521
0:46:15,000 --> 0:46:17,440
利泽德岛约九成的
About 90 percent of the branching corals

522
0:46:17,520 --> 0:46:19,880
珊瑚分支都死了
on the reef out here at Lizard Island are dead.

523
0:46:22,840 --> 0:46:25,520
它对另一种生活在这儿的生物
It also has disastrous consequences

524
0:46:25,600 --> 0:46:27,760
也造成了灾难性的后果
for the other creatures that live here.

525
0:46:31,320 --> 0:46:34,000
珀西在那里游泳
Percy swimming around out there.

526
0:46:34,120 --> 0:46:37,080
令人难过的是他的城堡开始白化了
The really sad thing is that his castle's starting to bleach.

527
0:46:38,360 --> 0:46:41,600
如果我们失去了珊瑚礁 我们也很可能会失去猪齿鱼
If we lose our coral, there's a chance we're going to lose our tuskfish

528
0:46:43,560 --> 0:46:47,160
当看到你从小潜水的地方
It's incredibly sad to see areas that you've dived on

529
0:46:47,240 --> 0:46:50,440
变成了一片废墟你真的会感到无比悲伤
since you were a little kid just turn to rubble.

530
0:46:53,600 --> 0:46:55,720
我在面具下哭了 当看到
I cried in my mask, when I saw,

531
0:46:55,800 --> 0:46:57,920
这种严重的白化情况时
you know, some of the devastation from this bleaching.

532
0:47:05,840 --> 0:47:07,720
在过去的三年里
In the last three years,

533
0:47:07,800 --> 0:47:10,720
全世界超过三分之二的珊瑚礁
over two-thirds of the world's coral reefs

534
0:47:10,840 --> 0:47:14,520
被认为在遭受海水升温的影响
are thought to have suffered from rises in ocean temperatures.

535
0:47:27,320 --> 0:47:29,680
这不是它们所面临的唯一挑战
This is not the only challenge they face.

536
0:47:32,360 --> 0:47:34,800
研究表明 海洋中的
Research is revealing how the fundamental

537
0:47:34,880 --> 0:47:37,160
基本化学反应正在改变
chemistry of the ocean is changing.

538
0:47:40,680 --> 0:47:43,880
克里斯 兰登教授通过将稀酸倒在贝壳上向我展示了
Professor Chris Langdon shows me what this might mean

539
0:47:43,960 --> 0:47:48,840
这对于海洋的未来意味着什么
for the future of our seas by pouring dilute acid over shells.

540
0:47:53,840 --> 0:47:57,480
这比我们现在的海洋酸性强多少
And how much more acidic is this than the present ocean?

541
0:47:58,120 --> 0:48:01,600
这个酸性比目前海洋的要强
This is more concentrated than the pH of the ocean

542
0:48:02,200 --> 0:48:05,480
但它加速了这个过程使其变的直观
but it accelerates the process so we can see something visually.

543
0:48:06,000 --> 0:48:09,280
看 这些贝壳发生了什么 它们是由碳酸钙组成的
So, what's happening is, these shells, they're made out of calcium carbonate,

544
0:48:10,000 --> 0:48:11,560
这些酸正在溶解它们
and the acid is dissolving them.

545
0:48:12,160 --> 0:48:15,920
珊瑚礁的组成和这些贝壳的材料是一样的
And coral reefs are made out of the same material as these shells here.

546
0:48:16,840 --> 0:48:20,840
但现在这肯定还没有发生 对吧
But surely this is not happening in the ocean now. Right now?

547
0:48:20,920 --> 0:48:24,400
只是我们现在看到的 要比海洋中实际的强烈而已
What we're seeing here is more dramatic than what's happening in the ocean.

548
0:48:24,480 --> 0:48:29,160
但是贝壳与珊瑚礁确实正在溶解
But the shells and the reefs are really truly dissolving.

549
0:48:29,240 --> 0:48:32,360
到本世纪末 珊瑚礁可能会消失
Coral reefs could be gone by the end of this century.

550
0:48:35,560 --> 0:48:39,040
这种现象的原因是什么 二氧化碳
And the cause of this? Carbon dioxide.

551
0:48:40,800 --> 0:48:44,280
它溶于水 形成碳酸
Dissolved in the sea water, it forms carbonic acid.

552
0:48:45,200 --> 0:48:47,720
大气中的二氧化碳越多
The more carbon dioxide in the atmosphere,

553
0:48:47,800 --> 0:48:50,120
海洋的酸性就越强
the more acidic the ocean becomes.

554
0:48:52,320 --> 0:48:55,120
证据表明化石燃料的燃烧
Evidence points to the burning of fossil fuels

555
0:48:55,240 --> 0:48:59,800
正是二氧化碳含量升高的主要原因
as the primary cause for these increasing levels of carbon dioxide.

556
0:49:01,640 --> 0:49:04,200
毫无疑问这是人类造成的
And this is man-made beyond question.

557
0:49:04,280 --> 0:49:05,480
确实毫无疑问
Beyond question.

558
0:49:09,600 --> 0:49:12,680
但是克里斯认为还为时未晚
But Chris believes all is not lost.

559
0:49:14,200 --> 0:49:18,160
我们最需要做的 就是减少二氧化碳的排放
All we have to do, and I say all, is reduce our CO2 emissions.

560
0:49:18,240 --> 0:49:22,360
我们可以用可再生能源 风能 太阳能
We can switch to renewable fuels, wind and solar,

561
0:49:22,440 --> 0:49:24,400
用来代替天然的矿物材料
instead of natural fossil fuels.

562
0:49:24,480 --> 0:49:26,160
这样 就不会
And so, none of this has to

563
0:49:27,080 --> 0:49:29,480
- 发展成最糟的情况 - 它还可以自我修复是吗
-develop to the worst case. -And that could fix it?

564
0:49:29,560 --> 0:49:34,160
是的 没错 这种情形是否出现在未来 这取决于我们
Yeah, absolutely. So, this future does not have to play out. It's up to us.

565
0:49:45,080 --> 0:49:48,680
随着气候的变化 海洋逐渐变暖
As the climate changes, the seas warm.

566
0:49:48,800 --> 0:49:51,680
我们的海洋受到了严重的影响
Our oceans are being seriously affected.

567
0:49:54,240 --> 0:49:58,560
没有什么地方比两极地区更明显了
And this is nowhere more apparent than at the poles.

568
0:50:07,520 --> 0:50:09,120
南极洲
Antarctica.

569
0:50:13,040 --> 0:50:17,560
对蓝色星球Ⅱ摄制团队来说 这是他们最壮志凌云的探险
For the Blue Planet II team, this was their most ambitious expedition.

570
0:50:20,240 --> 0:50:24,120
史上首次 一艘载人潜水器
For the first time in history, a manned submersible

571
0:50:24,200 --> 0:50:27,680
将会试着潜到水下1000米
will try to dive to a depth of 1,000 metres

572
0:50:27,760 --> 0:50:30,160
到达南极海底
and reach the Antarctic seabed.

573
0:50:31,560 --> 0:50:34,360
一次真正的未知之旅
A true journey into the unknown.

574
0:50:50,960 --> 0:50:54,240
控制探测器 已通过40米 结束
Control rover. Passing 40 metres. Over.

575
0:51:00,280 --> 0:51:03,240
带领团队进行这一历史性潜水的
Leading the team on this historic dive

576
0:51:03,320 --> 0:51:05,560
是深海科学家约翰 柯普利
is deep sea scientist John Copley.

577
0:51:13,360 --> 0:51:16,920
我们第一次看到这种景观
We get our first glimpse of this landscape.

578
0:51:19,640 --> 0:51:23,280
我们周围活跃的生命令人吃惊
And the carpet of life around us is astounding.

579
0:51:24,040 --> 0:51:25,320
太美了
It's beautiful.

580
0:51:34,280 --> 0:51:39,000
载人潜水器中的潜水经历让约翰
Diving in a submersible gives John an entirely new understanding

581
0:51:39,080 --> 0:51:41,760
对这个庞大生态系统的运作有了全新的认识
of how this rich ecosystem works.

582
0:51:43,480 --> 0:51:46,560
还给了他一个难得的机会
But it also offers him a unique opportunity

583
0:51:46,640 --> 0:51:49,560
调查这片海域是如何变化的
to investigate how the ocean here is changing.

584
0:51:50,840 --> 0:51:52,910
我们在观察那里的海洋生物时
While we're observing the marine life down there,

585
0:51:52,920 --> 0:51:55,200
潜水器也在记录周围的环境
the subs are also recording what the environment is like,

586
0:51:55,280 --> 0:51:57,640
我们得到温度 含盐度的测量值
so we're getting measurements of temperature, of salinity.

587
0:51:57,720 --> 0:52:00,000
希望这些数据能够帮助我们弄清
It's hopefully gonna enable us to understand the changes

588
0:52:00,080 --> 0:52:02,240
地球的这个重要地区所正发生的改变
that are happening in this vital part of our planet.

589
0:52:05,280 --> 0:52:07,880
为了得到更清晰的结果
To get a fuller picture, John also lowers

590
0:52:07,960 --> 0:52:10,200
约翰还下放了一个深海温度探测器
a deep sea temperature probe.

591
0:52:15,520 --> 0:52:19,200
他的数据有助于尝试绘制
His data is contributing to an international attempt

592
0:52:19,280 --> 0:52:22,920
国际间海平面与气温共同上升的图表
to chart the rise in both sea and air temperatures.

593
0:52:26,080 --> 0:52:28,240
在这里事物变化速度之快
What shocks me about what all the data show

594
0:52:28,360 --> 0:52:30,880
是数据分析中最令我吃惊的
is how fast things are changing here.

595
0:52:33,520 --> 0:52:36,320
我们正迈向未曾涉足的领域
We're headed into uncharted territory.

596
0:52:43,520 --> 0:52:45,560
为了真正地理解
To truly comprehend

597
0:52:45,640 --> 0:52:47,840
这里温度上升带来的影响
the effect of the temperature increases here,

598
0:52:47,920 --> 0:52:50,040
约翰坐上直升机
John takes to the skies.

599
0:52:51,200 --> 0:52:54,520
从那儿 他能够记录
From here, he can record the number and size

600
0:52:54,600 --> 0:52:59,080
从冰架上崩落的冰山数量和尺寸
of the icebergs being produced as the ice shelves melt and break apart.

601
0:53:01,640 --> 0:53:05,080
周围的冰山能够让我们明白
The bergs we're seeing all around us give you some idea

602
0:53:05,160 --> 0:53:09,520
南极正发生着多么大的变化
of how huge this process is that's taking place on the Antarctic.

603
0:53:10,840 --> 0:53:14,560
随着漂浮的冰架断裂
As the floating shelves break up, they allow water,

604
0:53:14,640 --> 0:53:18,120
会使原本存在了数千年的冰块融化成水
which has been locked up on land as ice for thousands of years,

605
0:53:18,200 --> 0:53:20,000
混入海洋中
to empty into the sea.

606
0:53:21,840 --> 0:53:25,080
据预测这会使海平面升高
And this is predicted to push up sea levels.

607
0:53:29,560 --> 0:53:32,760
冰架崩解 等于打开了泄洪闸
If the ice shelves break up, then that opens the flood gates.

608
0:53:33,600 --> 0:53:35,720
陆地上的冰会更快的流入海中
Ice on land flows faster into the sea

609
0:53:35,800 --> 0:53:37,440
使海平面上升
and that's what pushes up the sea levels.

610
0:53:39,360 --> 0:53:43,120
所以 这里发生的一切影响着我们所有人
So, what's happening here right now affects all of us.

611
0:53:57,520 --> 0:54:01,520
像迈阿密一样的城市已经处于威胁之中了
Already, cities like MiamI here are under threat.

612
0:54:02,400 --> 0:54:05,560
科学家们预测 到本世纪末
Scientists predict that by the end of the century,

613
0:54:05,640 --> 0:54:09,440
海平面将会上升一米甚至两米
the sea levels could have risen by a metre or even two.

614
0:54:10,080 --> 0:54:14,640
一旦成真 这座城市将会部分沉入水下
Were that to happen, parts of this city would certainly be submerged.

615
0:54:19,360 --> 0:54:23,920
全世界有亿万人住在海岸附近
Around the world, hundreds of millions of people live near the coast,

616
0:54:24,000 --> 0:54:28,520
由于海平面上升 他们的生活会受到严重影响
and as sea levels rise, their lives will be seriously affected.

617
0:54:41,760 --> 0:54:45,800
很明显我们的行动对世界海洋
It's now clear that our actions are having a significant impact

618
0:54:45,880 --> 0:54:47,640
有着巨大影响
on the world's oceans.

619
0:54:52,320 --> 0:54:55,760
在摄制这个系列纪录片的四年里
During the four years it took to make this series,

620
0:54:55,840 --> 0:54:58,920
我们最先见证了很多环境变化
we've witnessed many of these changes first-hand.

621
0:55:07,800 --> 0:55:10,880
但我们也和为了保卫海洋未来
But we've also worked alongside men and women

622
0:55:10,960 --> 0:55:14,720
而无私奉献的人们一同奋斗过
dedicating their lives to safeguarding the ocean's future.

623
0:55:22,200 --> 0:55:25,440
海洋为我们提供氧气
The oceans provide us with oxygen,

624
0:55:25,520 --> 0:55:27,480
调节气温
they regulate temperature,

625
0:55:27,560 --> 0:55:30,600
为我们提供食物和能源
they provide us with food and energy supplies.

626
0:55:31,240 --> 0:55:36,080
一个失去健康海洋的世界是不堪设想的
And it's unthinkable to have a world without a healthy ocean.

627
0:55:39,960 --> 0:55:42,720
我仍然相信我们有能力
I still think we have the capability

628
0:55:42,800 --> 0:55:45,880
去改变我们的行为 不再浪费资源
to change the manner in which we're wasting resources,

629
0:55:45,960 --> 0:55:47,920
毒害海洋
in which we're poisoning our oceans,

630
0:55:48,040 --> 0:55:51,600
就能期待一个有着健康海洋的未来
and we can look to a future with healthy oceans.

631
0:55:54,120 --> 0:55:58,600
我期许 我相信我们的所作所为
When I look forward, I believe that if what we are doing

632
0:55:58,680 --> 0:56:01,120
只要能被稍微效仿些许
can be duplicated just a little bit.

633
0:56:01,240 --> 0:56:04,080
这些动物们就有活下来的机会
These animals will have a chance of surviving.

634
0:56:05,640 --> 0:56:10,040
我想 这要取决于我们每个人
It comes down, I think, to us each taking responsibility

635
0:56:10,160 --> 0:56:12,760
为自己的选择承担责任
for the personal choices that we make in our everyday lives.

636
0:56:12,840 --> 0:56:15,680
希望我们每个人都能做到
That's all any of us can be expected to do.

637
0:56:15,760 --> 0:56:18,320
每天的选择累积起来就会有改变
And it is those everyday choices that add up.

638
0:56:33,760 --> 0:56:36,680
我们正处在历史上独一无二的时期
We are at a unique stage in our history.

639
0:56:37,600 --> 0:56:41,520
在此之前我们从未如此深刻地
Never before have we had such an awareness

640
0:56:41,600 --> 0:56:43,560
意识到我们在对这个星球做些什么
of what we are doing to the planet.

641
0:56:44,600 --> 0:56:49,640
之前我们也从未有过这样的力量去改变这种状况
And never before have we had the power to do something about that.

642
0:56:51,720 --> 0:56:55,560
毫无疑问 我们肩负着保护这个蓝色星球的责任
Surely, we have a responsibility to care for our blue planet.

643
0:56:56,680 --> 0:56:59,480
人类的未来
The future of humanity,

644
0:56:59,560 --> 0:57:02,800
以及地球上所有的生命
and indeed all life on Earth,

645
0:57:02,880 --> 0:57:05,160
此刻 都悬于我们一念之间
now depends on us.

646
